00:01:16.226 --> 00:01:18.545
So you could say that the
least common multiple,

00:01:18.545 --> 00:01:22.535
the LCM, of four and six

00:01:22.535 --> 00:01:24.545
is going to be,

00:01:24.545 --> 00:01:26.357
well, it's gonna be equal to,

00:01:26.357 --> 00:01:29.191
we're gonna have to have
the factors of both of them.

00:01:29.191 --> 00:01:32.665
So it's gonna have to have
two fours, two times two.

00:01:32.665 --> 00:01:34.488
It's gonna have to have a two and a three.

00:01:34.488 --> 00:01:35.705
Well we already have a two.

00:01:35.705 --> 00:01:36.896
In fact, we have to them.

00:01:36.896 --> 00:01:39.432
So in order to be divisible
by three, we have to be,

00:01:39.432 --> 00:01:41.461
in order to be divisible by six,

00:01:41.461 --> 00:01:44.277
we have to have three
as one of the factors.

00:01:44.277 --> 00:01:45.319
And so when you look at it that way,

00:01:45.319 --> 00:01:47.241
you say, "Hey look, we have to contain

00:01:47.241 --> 00:01:48.672
"all of the factors of each,"

00:01:48.672 --> 00:01:50.684
we have to have at least two twos

00:01:50.684 --> 00:01:52.993
and we have to have at least one three

00:01:52.993 --> 00:01:54.685
because the two twos
take care of this one too

00:01:54.685 --> 00:01:55.676
right over there.

00:01:55.676 --> 00:01:58.888
And you see that this is
also going to be equal to 12.

00:01:58.888 --> 00:02:00.393
Now when we think about
it for polynomials,

00:02:00.393 --> 00:02:02.235
we're gonna think about
it a little bit more.

00:02:02.235 --> 00:02:04.324
It's essentially the same idea,

00:02:04.324 --> 00:02:05.596
